</p><p>So we can discuss it:
</p><p>For a "medical opinion", from page 3:
</p>
<dl><dd>Girard sought advice from this then-girlfriend, a practicing psychologist, whom he declines to identify. He says she told him, "Nobody can become psychotic in their late 40s." She said he didn't seem to manifest other symptoms of psychotic behavior -- he dressed well, paid his bills -- and, besides his claims of surveillance, which sounded paranoid, he behaved normally.</dd></dl>
<p>The entire 4th and 5th pages cite verified research into governmental operations which verify that the technology possibly exists.  In fact, the majority of the article is dedicated to a first hand account of a group meeting, and listing possible technologies which could cause the symptoms described.  Out of a five page article, Wikipedia has chosen to source 1 line taken from three small paragraphs, out of a five page article, (approximately 2%) dealing with the medical opinion of the possibility that the group is suffering from a delusion, the vast majority of the content does not agree.  It's an obviously biased reading of the article, and not including at least some of the refutation which is papered all over the original work is improper and lacks integrity.  
</p><p>The content which I added, refers to technology listed and verified in the article, as well as in legislation in the US Congress.  Have you heard of MK-ULTRA?  Presenting the material the way it currently stands has the potential for grave social implications in the future; if this phenomenon ever does, even in a small way, turn out to be related to a government operation.  Even if it does not, the conclusions drawn in the WIkipedia article are completely unsupported in the sourced material.
</p><p>Specifically: "These are generally reported by external observers as being examples of belief systems, as opposed to reports of objective phenomena."  Is an uncited and generalized opinion.
</p><p>And: "Some psychiatrists and psychologists say web sites that amplify reports of mind control and group stalking are "an extreme community that may encourage delusional thinking" and represent a dark side of social networking. They may reinforce the troubled thinking of the mentally ill and impede treatment." is the only line sourced from an article which contains an overwhelming amount of information that supports a contrary view.
</p><p>Forgive me, but your comment that you get "delusional" in spades is a reflection of your opinion of these victims description of mind control, not a clear reflection of the cited work.
</p><p>From the fifth page,
</p><p><i>Meanwhile, the military's use of weapons that employ electromagnetic radiation to create pain is well-known, as are some of the limitations of such weapons.</i> In 2001, the Pentagon declassified one element of this research: the Active Denial System, a weapon that uses electromagnetic radiation to heat skin and create an intense burning sensation. So, yes, there is technology designed to beam painful invisible rays at humans, but the weapon seems to fall far short of what could account for many of the TIs' symptoms. While its exact range is classified, Doug Beason, an expert in directed-energy weapons, puts it at about 700 meters, and the beam cannot penetrate a number of materials, such as aluminum. <i>Considering the size of the full-scale weapon, which resembles a satellite dish, and its operational limitations, the ability of the government or anyone else to shoot beams at hundreds of people</i> -- on city streets, into their homes and while they travel in cars and planes -- <i>is beyond improbable.</i>
</p><p><i>But, given the history of America's clandestine research, it's reasonable to assume that if the defense establishment could develop mind-control or long-distance ray weapons, it almost certainly would. And, once developed, the possibility that they might be tested on innocent civilians could not be categorically dismissed.</i>
</p><p>I'd suggestion adding the italicized text, in order to remain at least somewhat unbiased.  Our government is not beyond reproach.<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:Contributions/65.7.161.239" title="Special:Contributions/65.7.161.239">65.7.161.239</a> (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User_talk:65.7.161.239" title="User talk:65.7.161.239">talk</a>) 04:45, 28 April 2013 (UTC)
