<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:Contributions/65.7.161.239" title="Special:Contributions/65.7.161.239">65.7.161.239</a> (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User_talk:65.7.161.239" title="User talk:65.7.161.239">talk</a>) 18:00, 28 April 2013 (UTC)
</p>
<dl><dd>My mental health has no bearing on this. My particular condition affects things such as my mood and concentration, but does not impair my cognition. I am in no way close to this issue because I had never heard of it until I came across attempts to present these delusions as fact on Wikipedia. As for the <i>Washington Post</i> article, some of it <i>is</i> about stalking, and presents gang stalking unequivocally as a delusion. The other content that you keep trying to insert in the article is about non-stalking aspects of mind control <i>etc.</i>, which, as Acroterion says, is not relevant to an article about stalking. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User:Phil_Bridger" class="mw-redirect" title="User:Phil Bridger">Phil Bridger</a> (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User_talk:Phil_Bridger" title="User talk:Phil Bridger">talk</a>) 20:48, 28 April 2013 (UTC)
<dl><dd>I'm not trying to insert anything.  You already have references to "psychotronic" weapons in the article, the only thing I am attempting to do is present an unbiased analysis of that topic.  If you continue to present the term, there is no reason not to be including information, from the same source, about it.  There is a reason it was including in the Post article, it's irresponsible to present your, or the author of a newspaper article's opinion as fact in an encyclopedia.  The entire point of including in the article, and in Wikipedia, is to remove bias.  <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User:Damonthesis" title="User:Damonthesis">Damonthesis</a> (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User_talk:Damonthesis" title="User talk:Damonthesis">talk</a>) 05:39, 29 April 2013 (UTC)
<dl><dd>Stop casting aspersions on other editors. My objection is to your lengthy discussion of psychotronic weapons, using the <i>Washington Post</i> article as a pretext, and your removal of references to delusional behavior.  In essence, you're trying to insinuate that these peoples' problems really <i>are</i> due to the use of some form of mind control. The concise mention already in the text about delusional behavior (extending to perceptions of persecution using unconventional means) is appropriate and supported by the <i>New York Times</i> and <i>Washington Post</i> references. Further expansion of the material would represent undue weight. The primary reference is the <i>Times</i> (which is mostly concerned with perceptions of stalking and mind control) and the secondary reference is the <i>Post</i>, which centers mainly on manifestations of delusional behavior. As I noted, the <i>Times</i> article is probably more useful, as it focuses on the phenomenon, while the <i>Post</i> article is a feature article mostly concerned with the victims of such delusions. They don't support a further discussion, and your campaign to remove the term "delusional" goes against those references. <b><font face="Arial"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User:Acroterion" title="User:Acroterion"><font color="black">Acroterion</font></a> <small><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User_talk:Acroterion" title="User talk:Acroterion"><font color="gray">(talk)</font></a></small></font></b> 13:48, 29 April 2013 (UTC)
<dl><dd>Really?  Please check the edit log again, I <i>removed nothing about delusional beliefs</i>, point in fact, I added to that argument as well.  All I did was follow WP:RS and include the other viewpoint presented in the sourced article.  Right now this page is in violation of that policy, <b>please see <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:RS" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:RS">WP:RS</a></b>.  My "campaign" has been to either remove the article in its entirety, or to add the secondary viewpoint, which is presented prominently in both the NY Times and Washington Post article.  This isn't really a discussion, the article as it stands does not properly present the content of the source. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User:Damonthesis" title="User:Damonthesis">Damonthesis</a> (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User_talk:Damonthesis" title="User talk:Damonthesis">talk</a>) 17:32, 29 April 2013 (UTC)</dd>
<dd>As far as "casting aspersions" please see the following page,<a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="https://groups.google.com/group/ffchs-daily-harassment-log/index/browse_frm/month/2010-11?_done=/group/ffchs-daily-harassment-log/browse_frm/month/2010-11?&amp;&amp;pli=1">https://groups.google.com/group/ffchs-daily-harassment-log/index/browse_frm/month/2010-11?_done=/group/ffchs-daily-harassment-log/browse_frm/month/2010-11?&amp;&amp;pli=1</a> In which <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User:Batvette" title="User:Batvette">User:Batvette</a> has 31 posts in a single month to a support group for "gang stalking."  Check out some of the comments, this user clearly has a vested interest in presenting a biased opinion from sourced material which does not. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User:Damonthesis" title="User:Damonthesis">Damonthesis</a> (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User_talk:Damonthesis" title="User talk:Damonthesis">talk</a>) 17:38, 29 April 2013 (UTC)
<dl><dd>As I said, you're abusing the <i>Post</i> article as a pretext for a long tangent on an unrelated subject, using speculation in the article to make the article on stalking into a coatrack for mind control theories. You've also demanded the removal of "delusion" (I'm assuming you're the IP above), despite its ample support by the sourcing and context of the article. The purely speculative passage, and therefore non-RS passage on mind control rays is one reason why I prefer the <i>Times</i> article as a more useful, straightforward source. And again, stop with the speculation about other editors. <b><font face="Arial"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User:Acroterion" title="User:Acroterion"><font color="black">Acroterion</font></a> <small><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User_talk:Acroterion" title="User talk:Acroterion"><font color="gray">(talk)</font></a></small></font></b> 17:55, 29 April 2013 (UTC)
<dl><dd>I'm not demanding the removal of anything.  I'm telling you that if the source is used, WP:RS demands that we provide both viewpoints presented in the source article, especially since the wikipedia article already contains references to "mind control rays."  I'm not sure why you are taking the position that the article should be sourced improperly, make a medical diagnosis based on the opinion of a news article, all contrary to Wikipedia policy.  About the Times article:
<dl><dd>"Although many Internet groups that offer peer support are considered helpful to the mentally ill, some experts say Web sites that amplify reports of mind control and group stalking represent a dark side of social networking. They may reinforce the troubled thinking of the mentally ill and impede treatment." is the paragraph sourced, and the only lines taken out support the viewpoint that "peer support can be helpful."  If you don't see this as a biased presentation of the source, you haven't looked at it.  In the same article this follows: <i>Mental health experts who have closely looked at the Web sites are careful to say that there is no way to prove if someone posting on, say, Mr. Robinson’s site, Freedomfchs.com, which says its mission is to seek justice for those singled out by “organized stalking and electromagnetic torture,” is suffering from mental illness.</i>  Again, the editors here are presenting a biased viewpoint that is specifically disproven in the source.  <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:RS" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:RS">WP:RS</a> states that even <i>minority viewpoints</i> need to be presented, and this is not that--it's a fact stated incontrovertibly in <i>your</i> source.</dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl>
<dl><dd><dl><dd><dl><dd><dl><dd><dl><dd><dl><dd><dl><dd>Both the Times and Post article present, after their analysis, information regarding legislators who have attempted to investigate or legislate regarding the "weapons" in question.  Yet this article represents neither.  In the Post it talks about Kucinich's bill, and in the Times article about Representative Jim Guest.</dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl>
<dl><dd><dl><dd><dl><dd><dl><dd><dl><dd><dl><dd><dl><dd>Guest's statement: “I’ve had enough calls, some from credible people — professors — being targeted by nonlethal weapons,” Mr. Guest said in a telephone interview, adding that nothing came of his request for a legislative investigation. “They become psychologically affected by it. They have trouble sleeping at night.” He added: “I believe there are people who have been targeted by this. With this equipment, you have to test it on somebody to see if it works.”  These people are United States Representatives and Senators, you cannot assume to put your personal opinion forward above theirs.</dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl>
<dl><dd><dl><dd><dl><dd><dl><dd><dl><dd><dl><dd><dl><dd>No matter how you slice it, you will not be able to properly source either article with the opinion that a large group of people is "delusional" when there is significant evidence in both articles, as well as the already sourced "Characteristics of False Stalking Reports" that clearly states well above 30% of these cases are <i>not the result of delusion.</i>  Again, misrepresenting the sourced newspaper articles, and using them to refute a published study you have already cited, <i>puts this 30% of real victims in danger</i>.  It is <i>not</i> a factual representation of any of the material cited. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User:Damonthesis" title="User:Damonthesis">Damonthesis</a> (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User_talk:Damonthesis" title="User talk:Damonthesis">talk</a>) 18:28, 29 April 2013 (UTC)</dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl>
<p>Just to summarize, you are representing the minority opinion of two news articles as the entirety of your source material for this section; you are presenting this minority opinion as fact, and refusing to include the opposing opinion presented in both articles.  This section is in gross violation of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:RS" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:RS">WP:RS</a>.   In addition, yourself, and two other editors have, over the course of <b>five years</b> continually argued to present this group of people as "suffering from a group delusion" despite numerous requests from the public to include the majority opinion in the articles cited:  that the delusional status of this group is questionable, the technology possibly exists, and numerous Federal legislators have not only agreed with the opinion that they are not delusional, but have presented legislation to ban the weapons and investigate "community Stalking."  The lack of inclusion of these facts presents a completely biased and uninformed opinion as a fact, which is held by a minority of Wikipedia editors. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User:Acroterion" title="User:Acroterion">User:Acroterion</a> himself, after reading the only sourced material on <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stalking" title="Stalking">Stalking</a> referring to "gang stalking", said that they were inappropriate for the stalking page, and subsequently insinuated that I was "championing" removing the information, while the only argument I have had was to follow <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:RS" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:RS">WP:RS</a>. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User:Damonthesis" title="User:Damonthesis">Damonthesis</a> (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User_talk:Damonthesis" title="User talk:Damonthesis">talk</a>) 18:48, 29 April 2013 (UTC)
</p>
